Suppose that the thickness of the interface layer under consideration is negligibly small compared with a fiber diameter. Taking average of strains and stresses with respect to a representative volume element (RVE), Figure 1, two fundamental formulas for a composite can be derived as (no additional assumption is made 
Figure 1.
A representative volume element (RVE) of a UD composite.

except that the fiber content is assumed to be the same before and after a load is applied to the composite):
(1){dɛi}=Vf{dɛif}+Vm{dɛim}
(2){dσi}=Vf{dσif}+Vm{dσim}
where Vf and Vm are the fiber and matrix volume fractions of the composite with Vf + Vm ≈ 1.

The RVE-averaged strain–stress relationships of the fiber, matrix and composite remain the same, i.e.,
(3){dɛif}=[Sijf]{dσjf}
(4){dɛim}=[Sijm]{dσjm}
(5){dɛi}=[Sij]{dσj}
where [Sijf] and [Sijm] are the instantaneous compliance matrices of the fiber and matrix, respectively, and [Sij] is that of the composite.

From equations (1)–(6), following equations are obtainable
(7){dσif}=(Vf[I]+Vm[Aij])-1{dσj}=[Bij]{dσj}
(8){dσim}=[Aij](Vf[I]+Vm[Aij])-1{dσj}=[Aij][Bij]{dσj}
(9)[Sij]=(Vf[Sijf]+Vm[Sijm][Aij])(Vf[I]+Vm[Aij])-1

If, however, the thickness of an interface layer cannot be neglected, a volume average with respect to a three-phase model shown in Figure 2 would result in the following equations:
(11){dɛi}=Vf{dɛif}+Vm{dɛim}+Vc{dɛic}
(12){dσi}=Vf{dσif}+Vm{dσim}+Vc{dσic}
Figure 2.
A matrix domain embedded with a fiber cylinder and interface layer subjected to a uniaxial tension.

where Vc is the volume fraction of the interface layer with Vf + Vm + Vc = 1. In addition to equations (3)–(5), there should be another stress–strain relationship for the interface layer, which is
(13){dɛic}=[Sijc]{dσjc}
